   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from sklearn.datasets import load_diabetes\n",
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "\n",
    "data = load_diabetes()\n",
    "df = pd.DataFrame(data.data, columns=data.feature_names)\n",
    "df['target'] = data.target\n",
    "df.head()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "00dd702d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": "## Fact\n\n### Which feature had the strongest correlation with disease progression? \n\n### Did patients with higher BMI generally show higher disease progression values? \n\n### Was blood pressure (bp) evenly distributed across patients? \n\n### Which feature showed the greatest variance? \n\n### Were there any obvious outliers in the dataset? "
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "1e69de5b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": "## Verification \n\n### Was BMI truly more important than age in predicting disease progression? \n\n### Did patients with higher blood pressure always experience more severe diabetes progression?\n\n### Were the cholesterol-related features (s1–s6) strongly correlated with each other? \n\n### Was the relationship between age and disease progression strong enough to be captured by a linear model? \n\n### Did feature standardization significantly affect model performance? \n\n### Did using all features necessarily produce better predictions than using only a few important features? \n\n### Did BMI and blood sugar related indicators (such as s5) jointly influence disease progression? "
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "3285b8df",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Exploratory\n",
    "\n",
    "If you could keep only one feature to predict disease progression, which would you choose and why?\n",
    "\n",
    "Would non-linear models such as Random Forest outperform linear models, and why? "
   ]
  }
 ],
